<img class="aligncenter wp-image-1294403 size-full" src="https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/China-trading.jpg?resize=640%2C345&#038;ssl=1" alt="NBS reveals capital importation into Nigeria declined by 7.7%" width="640" height="345" srcset="https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/China-trading.jpg?w=650&amp;ssl=1 650w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/China-trading.jpg?resize=300%2C162&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/China-trading.jpg?resize=58%2C31&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/China-trading.jpg?resize=260%2C140&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/China-trading.jpg?resize=200%2C108&amp;ssl=1 200w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/China-trading.jpg?resize=560%2C302&amp;ssl=1 560w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" data-recalc-dims="1" /> Fresh statistics released by National Bureau Of Statistics (NBS) on Monday revealed that the bulk of capital importation into Nigeria declined by 7.7%. The report shows that total value of capital importation into Nigeria stood at $5,367.56 million in 2019 third quarter (July to September). This represents a decrease of -7.78% compared to 2019 second quarter and 87.99% increase compared to the third quarter of 2018. The report added that the largest amount of capital importation by type was received through Portfolio investment, which accounted for 55.88% ($2,999.50million) of total capital importation. This is followed by Other Investment, which accounted for 40.39% ($2.167.98million) of total capital, and then Foreign Direct Investment FDI, which accounted for 3.73% ($200.08m) of total capital imported in Q3 2019. By sector, Capital importation by banking dominated 2019 third quarter reaching $1,756.83 million of the total capital importation in Q3 2019. Also, the report shows that the United Kingdom emerged as the top source of capital investment in Nigeria in Q3 2019 with $2,011.14million. “This accounted for 37.47% of the total capital inflow in Q3 2019.” By Destination of Investment, Lagos State emerged as the top destination of capital investment in Nigeria in 2019 third quater with $4,976.40 million. This according to the report accounted for 92.71% of the total capital inflow in  2019 third quater. Vanguard Nigeria News Foreign investment inflow into the Nigeria oil and gas industry declined sharply by 59.7 per cent to $133.51 million in 2018, compared to $331.36 million recorded in 2017, according to data obtained from the National Bureau of Statistics, NBS. February 26, 2019 In "Energy" National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) said that total Foreign Investment into the country rose by 34.6 percent year-on-year to $8.5 billion in the first quarter of the year (Q1'19). The Burea disclosed this in it's Capital Importation report for first quarter of 2019 released this morning. July 2, 2019 In "Business" The National Bureau of Statistics (NBS), said that the total value of capital importation into Nigeria stood at 8,485 million dollars in the first quarter of 2019. July 2, 2019 In "Business"